    slug: 'monocrystalline-vs-polycrystalline-vs-thin-film',
    title: 'Monocrystalline vs polycrystalline vs thin-film',
    h1: 'Monocrystalline vs polycrystalline vs thin-film — what actually differs',
    description: 'The honest technical comparison: efficiency, temperature behavior, cost, and what it means for your home system.',
    metaDescription: 'A practical comparison of monocrystalline, polycrystalline, and thin-film solar panels for residential use. What actually changes for your roof.',
    pillar: 'panels-and-equipment',
    datePublished: '2026-04-15',
    sections: [
      { heading: 'What the three categories mean', body: 'Monocrystalline silicon panels are made from a single (mono) crystal of silicon. Polycrystalline silicon panels are made from many crystals fused together. Thin-film panels are not crystalline silicon at all — they are made by depositing a thin semiconductor layer on a substrate. All three produce electricity from sunlight, but with different efficiency, cost, and behavior characteristics.' },
      { heading: 'Efficiency and space', body: 'Monocrystalline panels are the most efficient of the three at roughly 19%–23% module efficiency in 2026, depending on cell architecture (PERC, TOPCon, HJT, back-contact). Polycrystalline typically runs 15%–17%. Thin-film is around 10%–13%. Higher efficiency means more power per square foot of roof — important if you have a small or unusually shaped roof.' },
      { heading: 'Temperature coefficient', body: 'Panels lose efficiency as temperature rises above 25°C. Monocrystalline panels have a temperature coefficient around -0.30%/°C to -0.40%/°C. Polycrystalline is similar. Thin-film (especially CdTe) tolerates heat better and is sometimes preferred in very hot climates. The effect is real but rarely the dominant variable in a U.S. residential install.' },
      { heading: 'Cost and availability', body: 'Polycrystalline is the cheapest per panel and is widely available. Monocrystalline is more expensive per panel but produces more electricity per panel, so the cost-per-watt is often similar in practice. Thin-film is a niche residential product in 2026 in the U.S., with most installations using monocrystalline silicon.' },
      { heading: 'What this means for your home', body: 'For most U.S. residential roofs, the choice is monocrystalline silicon in some form. Differences within monocrystalline (TOPCon vs HJT vs back-contact) matter to the panel manufacturer\'s engineers but rarely change your roof economics meaningfully. Trust your installer to pick a panel in your budget tier from a reputable manufacturer with a strong warranty.' },
      { heading: 'Aesthetics', body: 'All-black monocrystalline panels are the most common residential aesthetic. Polycrystalline panels often have a slightly speckled blue appearance. Black-on-black and silver-frame options exist across categories. Aesthetics matter to many homeowners — talk to your installer about panel appearance during the design phase.' },
    ],
